That's an interesting categorization. There may also be people who oppose gay equality because that's how they were raised, and when pressed to explain why or to justify their opposition, they then turn to scripture for the justification. The source of their opposition may in fact be simply or primarily what they were taught about gay people since childhood....a set of unexamined assumptions, not necessarily a deep commitment to a particular interpretation of scripture. This may be a fourth category. These folks may harbor deep anti-gay sentiment, but its roots may be more cultural than religious, with religion as the later justification. Of course there is a long history of people debating the true meaning of scripture and its implications for public policy. There were passionate debates in the antebellum period over whether the Bible condoned slavery or condemned slavery. Today this is not an issue, because we have settled the question of slavery in the United States. In the early 19th century, the abolitionist interpretation of the Bible was the one that probably seemed to most people "an unconventional interpretation," and yet that interpretation won out over time. People can read the Bible many different ways, and conventional interpretations do change, of course. I think that people's interpretations of the Bible usually reflect their experiences in society and the beliefs they were taught coupled with their reading of scripture. We do not read scripture with neutral eyes. We read with the assumptions that we have been taught and in the context of the society in which we live. To the extent that Christians hear only that "homosexuality" is a sin and that gay people are condemned if they do not repent of their sin, these Christians are likely to believe that this is what scripture says. If and when alternate viewpoints are presented, these assumptions about gay people that many Christians bring to their reading of scripture are challenged. That will not necessarily lead people to change their thinking, but over time it may. And certainly NOT challenging people's assumptions about gay people simply leaves the assumptions intact.I think we have no choice but to challenge people's myths and stereotypes and assumptions about us gay people. I think this will prompt some anti-gay Christians, but not all, to rethink how they interpret scripture. This is why I think the Equality Rides are so powerful and why several conservative Christian colleges have barred the Equality Riders from their campuses and have had them arrested. The Equality Riders are young people, mostly Christians, who are bringing a message to young Christian conservatives that gay people are not as the myths and stereotypes suggest and that Christians should rethink how they interpret scripture when it comes to gay people. The Equality Riders thus challenge the assumptions that many people hold about gay people, assumptions that I think prompt many Christians to embrace an anti-gay interpretation of scripture.
