e allies now is the result of our long, mostly lonely struggle. For you to suggest that we are somehow remiss because we haven't overcome the repression of gay people everywhere in the world shows how little you understand the struggle we have gone through here, and the struggle we are still engaged in. You say that we are fighting for the right to marry with no consideration of the impact this will have. Of course we are considering the impact it will have. Our winning the right to marry will provide greater protections for our children and for our families. That's the impact it will have. Our having the right to marry will help our children. And our children matter just as much as the children of heterosexuals matter. I have a small daughter. I want her to have the same protections that heterosexual parents can provide for their children through legal marriage. Some people argue that we should be satisfied with civil unions, that everyone supports civil unions now, so why can't we be satisfied with that? It was just a few years ago that people went ballistic in Vermont over our winning the right to civil unions. Opponents of gay rights were outraged that we should get any state recognition at all for our relationships, and they threatened to vote the legislators who supported civil unions out of office. Now people say similar things about marriage. How dare we presume to argue that we should have the right to marry? The idea offends good heterosexual Christians! Well, too bad if heterosexual Christians are offended. My daughter matters more than whether someone else feels offended about my marriage. Our children and our families matter more than whether someone feels offended because they don't want us to be treated as equals. That's what this boils down to. The opponents of same-sex marriage refuse to allow gay people to be treated as equals. I am sick and tired of listening to the whining of anti-gay heterosexuals over how terrible it will somehow be for them or