hy in Scandinavia, where same-sex couples have had rights the longest. In Denmark, for example, the marriage rate had been declining for a half-century but turned around in the early 1980s. After the 1989 passage of the registered-partner law, the marriage rate continued to climb; Danish heterosexual marriage rates are now the highest they've been since the early 1970's. And the most recent marriage rates in Sweden, Norway, and Iceland are all higher than the rates for the years before the partner laws were passed. Furthermore, in the 1990s, divorce rates in Scandinavia remained basically unchanged.” Kurtz also claims that in Scandinavia, the numbers of unmarried heterosexual cohabiting couples have increased dramatically, as have births to unwed mothers, and for this he blames the legalization of same-sex marriage. But as Badgett points out, the increase in co-habitation between unmarried couples went up before the legalization of same-sex marriage, not afterward. And, according to Badgett, most co-habiting opposite-sex Scandinavian couples do marry after they have a child. He reports that 70% of co-habiting opposite-sex couples in Sweden marry after they have their first child. Badgett also reports that in the Netherlands, where same-sex marriage is legal, 90% of heterosexual couples with children are married. Kurtz's arguments are repeated ad nauseum in conservative publications to provide supposed "evidence" that same-sex marriage has led to the decline of heterosexual marriage. But examination of Kurtz's arguments quickly shows how absurd his claims are, and how he falsifies "evidence." I think he falsifies evidence deliberately. Kurtz knows better than to put forward such falsehoods as he does.
